Xenogenders do not mean that someone "identifies as" thing. Rather, they feel as though their gender is related to that thing, "inspired by" that thing, and similar experiences (which yes, is different than "identifying as" something).

Xenogenders are often used by [neurodivergent] people (people who are not neurotypical), because said people find them to be an easier way to describe their gender identity experience. And while there are neurogenders, which are exclusive to [neurodivergent] people/people which specific neurodivergencies, other xenogenders can be used by anyone and everyone, if they feel as though a certain label fits them.
